Kotlin null safety:

```kotlin
val name: String = "Sergio"     // Cannot be null — compiler enforces
val name: String? = null         // Nullable — must handle before use

// Safe call (returns null if name is null)
val length = name?.length        // Int? — might be null

// Elvis operator (default value)
val length = name?.length ?: 0   // Int — guaranteed non-null

// Smart cast (after null check, type narrows)
if (name != null) {
    println(name.length)  // Compiler knows it's non-null here
}
```

In Java, ANY reference can be null — you discover it at runtime (NPE in production). In Kotlin, the compiler tells you at write-time.

The `!!` operator forces a nullable to non-null (throws NPE if null) — using it defeats the purpose. Code reviews should flag `!!` usage.
